MENINGITIS, MENINGOCOCCAL - GERMANY: (BERLIN) FATAL, MEN WHO HAVE SEX WITH MEN, VACCINATION
*******************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sat 20 Jul 2013
Source: Zeit Online [in German, machine trans. edited]
http://www.zeit.de/wissen/gesundheit/2013-07/meningokokken-homosexualitaet-berlin/komplettansicht?print=true


Death came quickly, as is typical for this disease. A few weeks ago, on 8 May [2013] the 2 young men had been out with friends in Friedrichshain-Kreuzberg and visited a gay club. Two days later, both felt sick. One suffered from nausea, vomiting, and a stiff neck. A little later, he was admitted to the hospital and remains in a coma. The other went to work; in the evening, he met friends, but he felt worse. Two days later, he died in his apartment. A bacterium called _Neisseria meningitidis_ was isolated from both men.

Many people may carry these bacteria on the mucous membranes of nose and throat for months without becoming ill; the organism may then disappear. "20-30 per cent of young people in Germany may carry the pathogen," said Wiebke Hellenbrand, of the Robert Koch Institute (RKI). What distinguishes the healthy carrier from the sick, nobody knows.

How the 2 Berliners were infected is unclear. Meningococci are transmitted by droplet [aerosol or secretions from the nasopharynx of colonized persons]. Humans can be infected by kissing or coughing. "Maybe the 2 infected each other. Or maybe they were both infected by a 3rd party," said Ulrich Marcus of RKI. The exact route of the pathogen cannot be reconstructed but has led to investigations that have uncovered additional cases and a call to vaccinate some 80 000 men who have sex with men in Berlin.

Deaths caused by _N. meningitidis_ are not unusual. In Europe, the subgroups B and C are particularly responsible for causing illness, mostly in children and teenagers. In 2012, the Robert Koch Institute (RKI: the German national disease surveillance insitute) reported 300 ill, 33 of whom died.

"This case was really only noticed because these 2 men were diagnosed within 24 hours, and it was clear that they had spent the night together," said Hellenbrand. That sounds like an outbreak. Meningococcal infections tend to break out in places where people come together in a confined space: guests on a cruise ship, fans at a rugby game, kids at a carnival party.

And another thing made the RKI experts take notice: the 2 men were gay, or, as the RKI epidemiologists called them, MSM (men who have sex with men). Epidemiologists are concerned with behavior, not sexual orientation. MSM includes gays, as well as bisexuals and male prostitutes.

Actually, gays are not considered particularly vulnerable to meningococcal disease, which affects men and women, homo- and heterosexuals alike. But doctors in Toronto in 2001 described a small outbreak of meningococcal disease among MSM: six people developed the disease, and 2 of them died. This was followed by outbreaks in Chicago and Los Angeles. But doctors were really attentive only when an outbreak in New York City last year [2012] afflicted 22 gays, 7 of whom died.

And now Berlin: investigation revealed that a young gay man had come to the hospital in February [which year?] with meningococcal disease. He died 10 hours later in the operating room. Later in Berlin, 2 cases were yet to be identified, one died in October 2012, the other fell ill in February 2013 and survived.

Concerns have been expressed by the European Centre for Disease Control (ECDC). On 3 Jul 2013, ECDC experts published a brief risk assessment. They concluded that in big cities in Europe, there is an increased risk that gay men are infected with meningococcus and warned that huge gay festivals, such as the Christopher Street Day in Berlin, might contribute to the dissemination of the pathogen. Countries should, therefore, be particularly vigilant for meningococcal cases.

Why gays in particular? Don Weiss of the health department in New York, who experienced the outbreak in his own city, wonders whether the pathogen has changed and adapted to the group of MSM. Could meningococci be colonizing the urethra of gay men and be transmitted during oral sex? Or has the pathogen adapted to the anal mucosa? "We know that smoking is a risk factor, because it damages the lining of the airways and makes it easier for bacteria to enter the body," says White [Weiss?]. "The same could happen if the anal mucosa is irritated." Then, anal intercourse would be a risk factor.

Amanda Cohn of the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in Atlanta believes there is a simpler explanation: gays are a social group with close contacts and could, therefore, be affected like a school class. Many gay men have multiple sexual partners quickly, kiss in greeting, and go to crowded parties, which could magnify the problem. In one study, 43 per cent of gays carried the pathogen.

The question of whether a special strain of bacteria is circulating in the gay community must be examined in each case, says Ulrich Vogel from the National Reference Center for Meningococcal Disease at the University of Wurzburg. It would be possible to examine whether bacteria isolated from the Berlin patients grew better in intestinal mucosal cells or urethral cells than bacteria from other patients. Genetic sequencing of the Berlin strains is planned, and American and French researchers also want to sequence their samples. Perhaps a tiny change in the genetic material appears only in cases in MSM.

Marlen Suckau of the Berlin Impfbeirat [vaccination advisory board] had wide ranging discussions to decide whether the situation was disturbing enough for them to issue a recommendation for vaccination. In essence, vaccination would be recommended if a regional cluster were identified. For meningococcal disease, that means 10 cases per 100 000 people in one year. The group of MSM in Berlin is estimated at 80 000, and 5 cases in 10 months is significantly below the threshold. On the other hand, France had already issued a recommendation for vaccination and gays were vaccinated in New York and Chicago.

In the end, the Impfbeirat noted that the cases were all aged 20 to 29 years, says Suckau. In this age group, there are an estimated 18 000 MSM in Berlin. Thus, the threshold was exceeded in this group.

The recommendation is still valid for all MSM. "It's easier to communicate, and you cannot send away a 19 year old from a doctor's office," says Suckau. The recommendation was published in the Official Journal. On Sat 27 Jul 2013, it will come into force. For 6 months, gays will be eligible for vaccination in Berlin.

"This is a unique vaccine that is well tolerated," says Suckau, who wonders how high uptake will be. Germans have a hard time with vaccination -- for example, debating measles vaccination. Against the swine flu virus H1N1, only 5 per cent in Berlin were vaccinated, says Suckau. "So 20 per cent uptake for meningococcal vaccine would be a great success."

[byline: Kai Kupferschmidt]

