******
[2]
Date: Thu 18 Jul 2013
Source: Berlin.de/The Official Capital City Portal [in German, machine trans. edited]
http://www.berlin.de/sen/gessoz/presse/archiv/20130718.1630.387129.html


The Berlin Impfbeirat on 17 Jul 2013 has recommended an extension of public vaccination in Berlin, according to which men who have sex with men (MSM) should be vaccinated against meningococcal disease. The scheme is expected to start on 27 Jul 2013. The reason for the extended vaccination recommendation is an increased incidence of meningococcal disease among MSM in Berlin.

Of the total of 18 [cases of] meningococcal disease in Berlin in 2013, 7 were caused by group C _Neisseria meningitidis_. Of the latter, 3 patients died, and a 4th remains ill. These 4 patients are MSM and recent disease outbreaks among MSM have occurred in New York and Paris.

Meningococcal bacteria are found in the nasopharyngeal cavity in humans and can be transmitted by kissing, for example, or coughing. About 10 per cent of the population carry the bacteria without necessarily being ill. It is assumed that about 40 per cent of MSM are carriers of the bacteria and thus may be at higher risk of disease. The disease is taken very seriously, as it may be associated with serious complications and permanent damage. 2/3rds of affected patients suffer meningitis, and 1/3rd a life-threatening bloodstream infection (sepsis). In 10-20 per cent of cases, there are permanent sequelae. The mortality rate of group C meningococcal disease is as high as 10 per cent.

The only effective way to prevent meningococcal disease is vaccination. According to the recommendation of the Standing Committee on Vaccination at the Robert Koch Institute (STIKO), all children up to the age of 18 years should receive a single dose of vaccine against group C meningococcal infection. In adults, the STIKO recommends vaccination for certain people with immune deficiencies, such as those who are HIV positive, or for travelers to certain countries. The STIKO has not issued any recommendation for vaccination for MSM, but this gap is now closed due to the current events. The vaccine used for the current outbreak in MSM must contain a meningococcal group C component and be approved for adults. The vaccine is very well tolerated in general.

The recommendation for vaccination is planned to expire on 31 Jan 2014, and its effectiveness will be reviewed after this period. At the same time, the state of Berlin is committed to ensuring that the issues of vaccination for MSM by STIKO be uniform and thus cleared for other states.

